\begin_layout Standard
Computing models of solvents are broadly divided into two types: those treating
 the solvent as a continuous medium (implicit models) and those describing
 the individual solvent molecules (explicit models).
 In the continuum model, the solvent is characterized only by the dielectric
 constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and contains an artificial-shaped cavity.
 The explicit models can have more specific scales.
 Within the scope of classical mechanics, the most expensive method can
 be the flexible and polarizable explicit model, while in computational
 chemistry, less precise models often have wider usage (for example, the
 proteins are treated in the unity of residues).
 As the theory of liquids was firstly established for spherical atom-like
 solvent particles, the model adopted by the theory is a rigid molecule
 model, only depending on its position and orientation, i.
 e.
 there is no relative movement within the solvent particles.
 This approximation has been proven reasonable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Gray-Gubbins"

\end_inset

.
 In this section, we will give a brief introduction of the implicit model
 in order to facilitate later discussion on solvation free energy corrections.
 We will then focus on the rigid solvent models and give some 
\color red
(...)
\color inherit
 discussion on the limits of each approximation.
 The flexible and polarizable models will also be briefly mentioned.
\end_layout

