\begin_layout Subsection
Poisson-Boltzmann methods
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Poisson–Boltzmann-methods"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Poisson-Boltzmann equation (PBE) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "holst_1994_poisson"

\end_inset

 permits to calculate electrostatic potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\mathrm{elec}}$
\end_inset

 for the continuum model, such that electrostatic component of the free
 energy
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{\mathrm{elec}}=\frac{1}{2}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})V_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{\mathrm{elec}}=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i}Q(\mathbf{r}_{i})V_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r}_{i})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{q}$
\end_inset

 is the charge distribution of the continuous medium, or in a discrete partial
 charge description 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Maxwell-Gauss equation in SI units convention gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot D(\mathbf{r})=\dfrac{\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})}{\varepsilon_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\mathbf{r})=\varepsilon_{0}E(\mathbf{r})+P(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is the electric displacement field, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is the system polarization, 
\begin_inset Formula $E(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 the electric field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 the vacuum permittivity.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 can also be expressed in term of the position-dependent dielectric constant
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $D(\mathbf{r})=\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})E(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

, thus gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})E(\mathbf{r})=\dfrac{\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})}{\varepsilon_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

or in terms of electrostatic potential 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\left[\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})\nabla V_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r})\right]=-\dfrac{\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})}{\varepsilon_{0}}\label{eq:poisson}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This second-order differential equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poisson"

\end_inset

) is called the Poisson equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation cannot be solved analytically for complex geometries (such
 as protein), therefore, it is done numerically using numerical methods.
 Such methods are mentioned in for example the article of Roux and Simonson
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "roux_implicit_1999"

\end_inset

 or Holst 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "holst_1994_poisson"

\end_inset

.
 A density functional approach based on the minimization of polarization
 density can be equally used to solve this equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marchi_2001,Levy_2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the dielectric constant is independent of the position, eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poisson"

\end_inset

) becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla^{2}V_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r})=-\dfrac{\rho_{q}(\mathbf{r})}{\varepsilon_{0}\varepsilon}\label{eq:poisson-simple}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the charge distribution is a point charge, the solution of eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poisson-simple"

\end_inset

) reduces to the Coulomb interaction.
 
\color red
(How? Unity to be verified.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the solvent is ionic, the Poisson equation can be modified by taking
 into account a (thermal) Boltzmann distribution of ions in the solvent,
 leading to the Poisson-Boltzmann Equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{r}
\nabla\cdot(\varepsilon(\mathbf{r})\nabla\phi(\mathbf{r}))-\kappa^{2}\left(\dfrac{kT}{q}\right)\sinh\left(\dfrac{qV_{\mathrm{elec}}(\mathbf{r})}{kT}\right)=-4\pi\rho(\mathbf{r})\\
\kappa^{2}=\dfrac{8\pi q^{2}I}{kT}
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the ion charge, 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the ion strength of the solution, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa^{2}$
\end_inset

 factor is inversely related to the Debye-Hückel length.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Born / Onsager / Generalized Born models
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Born-/-Onsager"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simple geometries, the Poisson equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:poisson"

\end_inset

) can be solved analytically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest model is a spherical cavity.
 For a net charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in a cavity of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, the electrostatic free energy of a medium with a dielectric constant of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 is given by the Born model: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{\mathrm{elec}}(q)=-\dfrac{1}{8\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\left(1-\frac{1}{\varepsilon}\right)\frac{q^{2}}{2a}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the Born model is not fully capable to predict the solvent behavior
 in a lot of cases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jensen"

\end_inset

.
 Other similar models include Onsager model, in which a dipole point (characteri
zed by momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

) is put in a spherical cavity; and the Kirkwood model refers to a general
 multipole expansion in a spherical cavity; while the Kirkwood-Westheimer
 model arises for an ellipsoidal cavity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The generalized Born (GB) model is the superposition of several net charges
 in spherical cavities as Born model describes, with a similar formalism:
 
\color red
(Unity?)
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{\mathrm{elec}}=-\dfrac{1}{8\pi\varepsilon_{0}}\left(1-\frac{1}{\varepsilon}\right)\sum_{i}\sum_{j}\frac{q_{i}q_{j}}{f_{ij}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{ij}$
\end_inset

 depends on the internuclear distance and Born radii for each pair of atoms,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{ij}=\sqrt{r_{ij}^{2}-a_{i}a_{j}\exp\left(\frac{r_{ij}^{2}}{4a_{i}a_{j}}\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $r_{ij}$
\end_inset

 being the distance between the centers of atom 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GB model provides a very fast method, with rather the same accuracy
 compared to Poisson-Boltzmann calculations.
 That makes it widely used to perform optimization and simulations.
\end_layout

