 As the distance between the atoms decreases, the attractive electron-proton
 interactions dominate, and the energy of the system decreases.
 At the observed bond distance, the repulsive electron-electron and proton-proto
n interactions just balance the attractive interactions, preventing a further
 decrease in the internuclear distance.
 At very short internuclear distances, the repulsive interactions dominate,
 making the system less stable than the isolated atoms.
