\begin_layout Standard
The Lennard-Jones (LJ) interaction gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{LJ}(r)=4\varepsilon\left[\left(\frac{\sigma}{r}\right)^{12}-\left(\frac{\sigma}{r}\right)^{6}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 (of unity [
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Å}$
\end_inset

]) is the distance from central to central, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 (of unity [
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Å}$
\end_inset

]) is the collision diameter is the separation of particles where 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r)=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is the well depth of the potential (of unity 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{kJ/mol}$
\end_inset

).
 This well (the minimum) occurs at 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\min}=2^{1/6}\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r_{\min})=-\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 can be measured by experiment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Theoretically, all terms in the multipole series represent attractive contributi
ons to the potential.
 The leading term, varying as 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-6}$
\end_inset

, describes the dipole-dipole interaction.
 Higher-order terms represent dipole-quadrupole (
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-8}$
\end_inset

), quadrupole-quadrupole (
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-10}$
\end_inset

) interactions, and so on, but these are negligible compares to 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-6}$
\end_inset

.
 The short-range interaction is difficult to calculate, and it's defined
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{-12}$
\end_inset

 in the LJ model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The electrostatic interaction between two charged particles 1 and 2 is described
 by the Coulomb point charge interaction:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{\mathrm{Coul}}(r)=\frac{q_{1}q_{2}}{4\pi\varepsilon_{0}r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generally, the pair potential for atomic particles 
\begin_inset Formula $u(r)$
\end_inset

 used is a sum of LJ and Coulomb interactions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Molecular fluid model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As discussed before, atomic description of interactions is not sufficient
 to well describe solvation properties.
 For polar liquids, the dipole-dipole interaction should be mainly taken
 into account.
 It can be superposed onto the spherically symmetric potential:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(1,2)=u_{0}(r)-\boldsymbol{\mu}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{r})\cdot\boldsymbol{\mu}_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 is the vector separation of the molecular centers, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}(r)$
\end_inset

 is the spherically symmetric term as discussed above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mu}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the dipole moment vector of particle 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{r})$
\end_inset

 is the dipole-dipole interaction tensor:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T(\mathbf{r})=\nabla^{2}\left(\dfrac{1}{r}\right)=3\mathbf{r}\mathbf{r}/r^{5}-\mathbf{I}/r^{3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}$
\end_inset

 is the unit tensor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The site-site model is a further extension of atomic model, in which the
 solvent molecule is represented by a set of discrete interaction sites.
 The total potential energy is a sum of spherical interaction potentials:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(1,2)=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{\alpha}\sum_{\beta}u_{\alpha\beta}(\left|\mathbf{r}_{2\beta}-\mathbf{r}_{1\alpha}\right|)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{is}$
\end_inset

 is the coordinates of site 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in molecule 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\alpha\beta}(r)$
\end_inset

 the interatomic potential energy of pair of sites 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, as discussed above.
 This model is the mostly adopted, as well as in this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full formalism of molecular fluid is 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\mathbf{r}_{12},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})$
\end_inset

